This paper presents a novel textual reply generation model that takes into account the content preferences of the user, the idiosyncrasies of their conversational style, and even the structure of their social graph. This work involves natural language processing, machine learning, and social network analysis, which are all relevant to the computer science sub-categories of computational linguistics (cs.CL), social and information networks (cs.SI), machine learning (cs.LG), information retrieval (cs.IR), and artificial intelligence (cs.AI).
